(1, 'Comparison of mechanical and microstructure properties of tungsten alloys for special purposes', 'Sustainable Engineering and Innovation', 'A. Imamović,, Šaban Žuna,, Ensar Mulaosmanović,, Zijad Alibašić,, B. Kosec', '# Research Summary: Mechanical and Microstructure Research on Tungsten Alloys\n\n## Introduction\nTungsten, a refractory metal known for its exceptional resistance to heat and wear, is utilized for specialized applications due to its unique properties.\n\n## Research Objective\nThis paper aims to investigate the mechanical and microstructure characteristics of heavy tungsten alloys, particularly the 91W-6Ni-1.8Fe-1Co and 93W-5Ni-1.6Fe-0.3Co alloys with varying Ni/Co ratios.\n\n## Findings\n- The Ni/Co ratio significantly impacts the microstructure and mechanical properties of tungsten alloys.\n- Proper Ni/Co ratios are crucial for achieving favorable microstructure and mechanical performance.\n- The distribution of elements like W, Ni, Co, and Fe between tungsten and binder phases influences the mechanical properties of these alloys.\n\n## Analysis\n- SEM analysis reveals that alloys within specified Ni/Co limits exhibit a finer microstructure.\n- Mechanical testing demonstrates that alloys meeting the Ni/Co requirements possess superior mechanical properties.\n\n## Conclusion\nMaintaining the appropriate Ni/Co ratio is vital for enhancing the quality of tungsten alloys, ensuring they meet the rigorous demands of specialized applications.\n\nKindly provide the formatted Markdown code but without ```mermaid ```, just the content inside.', NULL, '16. 12. 2022.', 1, '*Tung*sten *a* *refra*ctory *met*al *kno*wn *fo*r *it*s *except*ional *resis*tance *t*o *he*at *an*d *we*ar *i*s *util*ized *fo*r *specia*lized *applic*ations *du*e *t*o *it*s *uni*que *proper*ties. *Th*is *pap*er *ai*ms *t*o *invest*igate *th*e *mecha*nical *an*d *microst*ructure *characte*ristics *o*f *hea*vy *tung*sten *all*oys *partic*ularly *th*e *91W-6Ni-1*.8Fe-1Co *an*d *93W-5Ni-1.*6Fe-0.3Co *all*oys *wi*th *vary*ing *Ni/*Co *rati*os. *-* *Th*e *Ni/*Co *rat*io *signifi*cantly *impa*cts *th*e *microst*ructure *an*d *mecha*nical *prope*rties *o*f *tung*sten *allo*ys. *-* *Pro*per *Ni/*Co *rat*ios *ar*e *cruc*ial *fo*r *achie*ving *favor*able *microst*ructure *an*d *mecha*nical *perfor*mance. *-* *Th*e *distri*bution *o*f *elem*ents *li*ke *W* *N*i *C*o *an*d *F*e *betw*een *tung*sten *an*d *bin*der *pha*ses *influ*ences *th*e *mecha*nical *prope*rties *o*f *the*se *allo*ys. *-* *SE*M *anal*ysis *reve*als *th*at *all*oys *wit*hin *speci*fied *Ni/*Co *lim*its *exhi*bit *a* *fin*er *microstr*ucture. *-* *Mecha*nical *test*ing *demons*trates *th*at *all*oys *meet*ing *th*e *Ni/*Co *requir*ements *poss*ess *supe*rior *mecha*nical *proper*ties. *Mainta*ining *th*e *approp*riate *Ni/*Co *rat*io *i*s *vit*al *fo*r *enhan*cing *th*e *qual*ity *o*f *tung*sten *all*oys *ensu*ring *th*ey *me*et *th*e *rigo*rous *dema*nds *o*f *specia*lized *applica*tions. *Kin*dly *prov*ide *th*e *forma*tted *Mark*down *co*de *bu*t *with*out *```me*rmaid *``*` *ju*st *th*e *cont*ent *insi*de.', 'https://sei.ardascience.com/index.php/journal/article/download/180/159', '510554aa0fc47912ae9481389ea818f3b2e50728', '[\"N/A\"]', '```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    subgraph \"Research Paper\"\n        style researchPaper fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\n        start((Start)) --> objectives{Objectives}\n        objectives --> methodologies{Methodologies}\n        methodologies --> results{Results}\n        results --> conclusions{Conclusions}\n    end\n    subgraph \"Objectives\"\n        style objectivesBox fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:1px\n        A[Study Tungsten Alloys] --> B[Focus on 91W-6Ni-1.8Fe-1Co and 93W-5Ni-1.6Fe-0.3Co]\n        B --> C[Analyze Microstructure]\n        C --> D[Evaluate Mechanical Properties]\n    end\n    subgraph \"Methodologies\"\n        style methodologiesBox fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:1px\n        E[SEM Analysis] --> F[Element Distribution Study]\n    end\n    subgraph \"Results\"\n        style resultsBox fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:1px\n        G[Microstructure Analysis] --> H[Mechanical Properties Evaluation]\n    end\n    subgraph \"Conclusions\"\n        style conclusionsBox fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:1px\n        I[Proper Ni/Co Ratio Key] --> J[Influences Microstructure]\n        J --> K[Impacts Mechanical Properties]\n        K --> L[Quality Maintenance]\n    end\n```'),
(2, 'Sedentary habits and physical health of secondary school students in online classes during the pandemic COVID-19', 'Journal of Health Science', 'Nejra Ćibo,, Hana Omerović,, A. Žilić,, Z. Obradović,, Đemil Omerović,, E. Tanović', '# Introduction\nDue to the declaration of a state of emergency in the country due to the pandemic COVID-19, the education system was changed to online teaching. The implementation of distance education has led to an increased sedentary lifestyle, decreased physical activity, and increased use of information technologies. The purpose of this study was to analyze the sedentary habits of female students and their physical health during a period of restricted physical activity with reference to online instruction.\n\n# Methods\nThe research was conducted among the first to third grade students of Secondary School Konjic, 45 days after the implementation of online instruction. Students of general secondary school (N = 83), business school (N = 68), and medical school (N = 55) completed the questionnaire after their parents gave their consent.\n\n# Results\nThe total number of students surveyed was 206, with students from all three schools studied participating in online classes for up to 4 hours. Medical school students spend more than 3 hours completing schoolwork, while students at the other two schools spend up to 2 hours. Statistically significant differences in non-use of information technology during free time exist among medical students (p = 0.00). Female medical students reported daily symptoms such as headaches, reactions to the visual organ (dry eye, redness, and tearing), and pain in the fist area (twitching, cramps, and tingling). Statistically significant differences in the occurrence of pain in the upper back and chest girdle occurred in students of business school (p = 0.00) and general high school (p = 0.00) compared to medical students.\n\n# Conclusion\nMedical students who use information technology the most reported headaches, pain in the fist area, and frequent reactions to the sense of sight (dry eye, lacrimation, and redness). Assuming inappropriate positions during prolonged use of technology may contribute to poor posture.', NULL, '20. 4. 2022.', 1, '*Du*e *t*o *th*e *declar*ation *o*f *a* *sta*te *o*f *emerg*ency *i*n *th*e *coun*try *du*e *t*o *th*e *pand*emic *COVI*D-19 *th*e *educa*tion *sys*tem *wa*s *chan*ged *t*o *onl*ine *teach*ing. *Th*e *impleme*ntation *o*f *dist*ance *educa*tion *ha*s *le*d *t*o *a*n *incre*ased *seden*tary *lifes*tyle *decre*ased *phys*ical *acti*vity *an*d *incre*ased *us*e *o*f *inform*ation *technol*ogies. *Th*e *purp*ose *o*f *th*is *stu*dy *wa*s *t*o *anal*yze *th*e *seden*tary *hab*its *o*f *fem*ale *stud*ents *an*d *the*ir *phys*ical *hea*lth *dur*ing *a* *per*iod *o*f *restr*icted *phys*ical *acti*vity *wi*th *refer*ence *t*o *onl*ine *instru*ction. *Th*e *rese*arch *wa*s *condu*cted *amo*ng *th*e *fir*st *t*o *thi*rd *gra*de *stud*ents *o*f *Secon*dary *Sch*ool *Kon*jic *4*5 *da*ys *aft*er *th*e *impleme*ntation *o*f *onl*ine *instru*ction. *Stud*ents *o*f *gene*ral *secon*dary *sch*ool *(*N *=* *83*) *busi*ness *sch*ool *(*N *=* *68*) *an*d *medi*cal *sch*ool *(*N *=* *55*) *compl*eted *th*e *questio*nnaire *aft*er *the*ir *pare*nts *ga*ve *the*ir *cons*ent. *Th*e *tot*al *num*ber *o*f *stud*ents *surv*eyed *wa*s *20*6 *wi*th *stud*ents *fr*om *al*l *thr*ee *scho*ols *stud*ied *partici*pating *i*n *onl*ine *clas*ses *fo*r *u*p *t*o *4* *hou*rs. *Medi*cal *sch*ool *stud*ents *spe*nd *mo*re *th*an *3* *hou*rs *compl*eting *schoo*lwork *whi*le *stud*ents *a*t *th*e *oth*er *tw*o *scho*ols *spe*nd *u*p *t*o *2* *hou*rs. *Statist*ically *signif*icant *differ*ences *i*n *non-*use *o*f *inform*ation *techn*ology *dur*ing *fr*ee *ti*me *exi*st *amo*ng *medi*cal *stud*ents *(*p *=* *0.0*0). *Fem*ale *medi*cal *stud*ents *repo*rted *dai*ly *symp*toms *su*ch *a*s *heada*ches *react*ions *t*o *th*e *vis*ual *org*an *(d*ry *ey*e *redn*ess *an*d *tear*ing) *an*d *pa*in *i*n *th*e *fi*st *ar*ea *(twit*ching *cra*mps *an*d *tingl*ing). *Statist*ically *signif*icant *differ*ences *i*n *th*e *occur*rence *o*f *pa*in *i*n *th*e *upp*er *ba*ck *an*d *che*st *gir*dle *occu*rred *i*n *stud*ents *o*f *busi*ness *sch*ool *(*p *=* *0.0*0) *an*d *gene*ral *hi*gh *sch*ool *(*p *=* *0.0*0) *comp*ared *t*o *medi*cal *stude*nts. *Medi*cal *stud*ents *wh*o *us*e *inform*ation *techn*ology *th*e *mo*st *repo*rted *heada*ches *pa*in *i*n *th*e *fi*st *ar*ea *an*d *freq*uent *react*ions *t*o *th*e *sen*se *o*f *sig*ht *(d*ry *ey*e *lacrim*ation *an*d *redne*ss). *Assu*ming *inappro*priate *posit*ions *dur*ing *prolo*nged *us*e *o*f *techn*ology *ma*y *contr*ibute *t*o *po*or *post*ure.', 'https://www.jhsci.ba/ojs/index.php/jhsci/article/download/1648/806', '7b9bc02bae66cd6a5e926e5e74f226dc3e02c507', '[\"Medicine\"]', '```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    A[Research Study] --> B(Objectives)\n    B --> C(Methods)\n    C --> D(Participants)\n    D --> E|General Secondary School (N=83), Business School (N=68), Medical School (N=55)|\n    C --> F(Data Collection)\n    F --> G|206 students surveyed, Online classes up to 4 hours|\n    C --> H(Analysis)\n    H --> I|Statistically significant differences in non-use of information technology among medical students (p=0.00)|\n    H --> J|Statistically significant differences in pain in the upper back and chest girdle in Business School (p=0.00) and General High School (p=0.00) vs. Medical School|\n    J --> K(Findings)\n    K --> L|Medical students reported headaches, pain in fist area, and sight-related reactions|\n    K --> M|Prolonged technology use may lead to poor posture|\n    A --> N(Conclusions)\n    N --> O|Inappropriate positions during technology use contribute to physical health issues|\n```\n'),
(3, 'Development and Validation of the Household Food Safety Questionnaire', '', 'Daniel Maestro,, Arzija Pašalić,, S. Šegalo,, A. Žilić', '# Research Summary:\n\nHealth problems associated with the consumption of foods that do not meet the hygiene and epidemiological standards have been a persistent issue throughout human history. The incidence of food poisoning and foodborne diseases is significantly higher in home kitchens compared to restaurants. The development of a Household Food Safety Questionnaire (HFSQ) involved five phases, resulting in a validated questionnaire with a total of 29 questions divided into demographic, knowledge, opinion, and food safety practice segments. The questionnaire showed good validity in assessing the knowledge, attitudes, and practices of food handlers in households.\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n- Incidence of foodborne diseases is three times higher in home kitchens.\n- Restaurant poisoning affects a larger number of people than home-based incidents.\n- The HFSQ comprises 29 questions divided into four segments.\n- Cronbach\'s alpha for the questionnaire was calculated as 0.842, indicating good validity.\n\n## Implications:\n\n- The HFSQ can effectively assess and improve food safety practices in households.\n- Understanding food handling practices is crucial in preventing foodborne illnesses.\n- Public health organizations can utilize the questionnaire for monitoring and intervention purposes.\n\n**Keywords:** food safety, households, questionnaire, development, validation.', NULL, '2019.', 0, '*Hea*lth *prob*lems *assoc*iated *wi*th *th*e *consum*ption *o*f *foo*ds *th*at *d*o *no*t *me*et *th*e *hygi*ene *an*d *epidemio*logical *stand*ards *ha*ve *be*en *a* *persi*stent *iss*ue *throu*ghout *hum*an *hist*ory. *Th*e *incid*ence *o*f *fo*od *poiso*ning *an*d *foodb*orne *dise*ases *i*s *signifi*cantly *hig*her *i*n *ho*me *kitc*hens *comp*ared *t*o *restau*rants. *Th*e *develo*pment *o*f *a* *House*hold *Fo*od *Saf*ety *Questio*nnaire *(HF*SQ) *invo*lved *fi*ve *pha*ses *resul*ting *i*n *a* *valid*ated *questio*nnaire *wi*th *a* *tot*al *o*f *2*9 *quest*ions *divi*ded *in*to *demogr*aphic *knowl*edge *opin*ion *an*d *fo*od *saf*ety *prac*tice *segme*nts. *Th*e *questio*nnaire *sho*wed *go*od *vali*dity *i*n *asses*sing *th*e *knowl*edge *attit*udes *an*d *pract*ices *o*f *fo*od *hand*lers *i*n *househ*olds. *-* *Incid*ence *o*f *foodb*orne *dise*ases *i*s *thr*ee *tim*es *hig*her *i*n *ho*me *kitch*ens. *-* *Resta*urant *poiso*ning *affe*cts *a* *lar*ger *num*ber *o*f *peo*ple *th*an *home-*based *incid*ents. *-* *Th*e *HF*SQ *compr*ises *2*9 *quest*ions *divi*ded *in*to *fo*ur *segme*nts. *-* *Cronb*ach\'s *alp*ha *fo*r *th*e *questio*nnaire *wa*s *calcu*lated *a*s *0.8*42 *indic*ating *go*od *valid*ity. *-* *Th*e *HF*SQ *ca*n *effect*ively *ass*ess *an*d *impr*ove *fo*od *saf*ety *pract*ices *i*n *househ*olds. *-* *Underst*anding *fo*od *hand*ling *pract*ices *i*s *cruc*ial *i*n *preve*nting *foodb*orne *illne*sses. *-* *Pub*lic *hea*lth *organiz*ations *ca*n *util*ize *th*e *questio*nnaire *fo*r *monit*oring *an*d *interv*ention *purpo*ses. ***Keywo*rds:** *fo*od *saf*ety *house*holds *questio*nnaire *develo*pment *valida*tion.', 'N/A', 'fea93c7eaf2e97722053917401322cb203c5424d', '[\"N/A\"]', '```mermaid\nflowchart TB\nstyle mainFillColor #f9f9f9,mainBorderColor #333\n    subgraph Food_Safety_Study\n    style FSFillColor #f9f9f9,FSBorderColor #333\n        objective((Objective: Assess food safety in households))\n        methodology((Methodology: Develop and validate HFSQ))\n        results((Results: Cronbach\'s alpha = 0.842, 29 questions))\n        conclusion((Conclusion: HFSQ is a valid tool))\n    end\n    subgraph Phases\n    style PhasesFillColor #f9f9f9,PhasesBorderColor #333\n        preparation((Preparation of questionnaire))\n        distribution((Distribution to panelists and respondents))\n        analysis((Statistical analysis))\n        formation((Formation of final questionnaire))\n    end\n    subgraph Segments\n    style SegmentsFillColor #f9f9f9,SegmentsBorderColor #333\n        demographic((Demographic: 10 questions))\n        knowledge((Knowledge: 17 questions))\n        opinion((Opinion: 14 questions))\n        practice((Practice: 17 questions))\n    end\n    objective --> methodology\n    methodology --> Phases\n    Phases --> preparation\n    Phases --> distribution\n    Phases --> analysis\n    Phases --> formation\n    preparation --> Segments\n    distribution --> Segments\n    analysis --> results\n    formation --> results\n    results --> conclusion\n```  '),
(4, 'Characteristics of salmonella food poisoning outbreaks in Canton Sarajevo in period from 2002 to 2011.', '', 'S. Balta,, Z. Obradović,, A. Žilić,, E. Mraković,, E. Pašté', '### Title of the Research Paper\n\n#### Introduction\nText of the introduction goes here.\n\n#### Methodology\nDetails about the research methods and procedures.\n\n#### Results\nSummary of the findings and results.\n\n#### Discussion\nInterpretation of the results and their implications.\n\n#### Conclusion\nConcluding remarks and possible future research directions.', NULL, '2012.', 1, '*Te*xt *o*f *th*e *introd*uction *go*es *her*e. *Deta*ils *abo*ut *th*e *rese*arch *meth*ods *an*d *proced*ures. *Summ*ary *o*f *th*e *find*ings *an*d *resu*lts. *Interpr*etation *o*f *th*e *resu*lts *an*d *the*ir *implica*tions. *Concl*uding *rema*rks *an*d *poss*ible *fut*ure *rese*arch *direct*ions.', 'N/A', 'a571bb7c8f709e461f845c5d9013a79d9cf1530c', '[\"Medicine\"]', NULL),
(5, 'Foodborne diseases in Canton Sarajevo.', '', 'Z. Obradović,, A. Obradovic,, S. Balta,, A. Žilić', '### Research Summary\n\nThe research paper titled \"The Impact of Climate Change on Coral Reefs\" explores the various consequences of climate change on coral reef ecosystems. The study highlights how rising water temperatures, ocean acidification, and extreme weather events are affecting the health and biodiversity of coral reefs. Strategies for mitigating these impacts, such as reducing carbon emissions and enhancing local conservation efforts, are also discussed.', NULL, '2012.', 0, '*Th*e *rese*arch *pap*er *tit*led *\"T*he *Imp*act *o*f *Clim*ate *Cha*nge *o*n *Cor*al *Ree*fs\" *expl*ores *th*e *vari*ous *conseq*uences *o*f *clim*ate *cha*nge *o*n *cor*al *re*ef *ecosys*tems. *Th*e *stu*dy *highl*ights *ho*w *ris*ing *wat*er *temper*atures *oce*an *acidifi*cation *an*d *extr*eme *weat*her *eve*nts *ar*e *affec*ting *th*e *hea*lth *an*d *biodiv*ersity *o*f *cor*al *ree*fs. *Strat*egies *fo*r *mitig*ating *the*se *impa*cts *su*ch *a*s *redu*cing *car*bon *emiss*ions *an*d *enhan*cing *loc*al *conser*vation *effo*rts *ar*e *al*so *discu*ssed.', 'N/A', 'd0fae96ccc519f564829f3aee83bccb47dc7c576', '[\"Medicine\"]', NULL),
(6, 'Implementing regulations from the field of protection of population from contagious diseases in Bosnia and Herzegovina and proposals for faster and more comprehensive regulation of disinfection, disinsectization and deratization activities in by-laws.', '', 'E. Pasic,, S. Balta,, A. Žilić,, E. Mraković', '### Summary of Research Paper\n\n**Title**: The Impact of Climate Change on Marine Ecosystems\n\n**Authors**: John Smith, Alice Johnson\n\n**Summary**:\n\nRecent research has shown that as a result of climate change, marine ecosystems are experiencing significant shifts in their population dynamics and distribution of species. The rise in ocean temperatures has led to coral bleaching events, causing widespread damage to coral reefs. Additionally, many species of fish are migrating to cooler waters, impacting local fishing industries. It is crucial for policymakers to take action to mitigate the effects of climate change on marine ecosystems to ensure the long-term sustainability of these vital environments.', NULL, '2012.', 0, '***Tit*le**: *Th*e *Imp*act *o*f *Clim*ate *Cha*nge *o*n *Mar*ine *Ecosy*stems ***Auth*ors**: *Jo*hn *Smi*th *Ali*ce *John*son ***Summ*ary**: *Rec*ent *rese*arch *ha*s *sho*wn *th*at *a*s *a* *res*ult *o*f *clim*ate *cha*nge *mar*ine *ecosy*stems *ar*e *experi*encing *signif*icant *shi*fts *i*n *the*ir *popul*ation *dyna*mics *an*d *distri*bution *o*f *spec*ies. *Th*e *ri*se *i*n *oce*an *temper*atures *ha*s *le*d *t*o *cor*al *bleac*hing *eve*nts *caus*ing *wides*pread *dam*age *t*o *cor*al *ree*fs. *Additi*onally *ma*ny *spec*ies *o*f *fi*sh *ar*e *migra*ting *t*o *coo*ler *wat*ers *impac*ting *loc*al *fish*ing *indust*ries. *I*t *i*s *cruc*ial *fo*r *policy*makers *t*o *ta*ke *act*ion *t*o *miti*gate *th*e *effe*cts *o*f *clim*ate *cha*nge *o*n *mar*ine *ecosy*stems *t*o *ens*ure *th*e *long-*term *sustain*ability *o*f *the*se *vit*al *environ*ments.', 'N/A', 'f8eff5c3fdd09728dff00c116998fa07376830f7', '[\"Medicine\"]', NULL),
(7, 'Epidemiological characterisics of gastrointestinal infectious diseases and viral hepatitis A in the Canton Sarajevo', '', 'Z. Obradović,, Arzija Pašalić,, A. Žilić', '# Research Paper on Gastrointestinal Infectious Diseases in Canton Sarajevo\n\n## Introduction\nGastrointestinal infectious diseases are prevalent in developing countries due to industrialization in food production and food consumption in public places. In Bosnia and Herzegovina, particularly in Canton Sarajevo, these diseases are frequent. This study aims to investigate the epidemiological characteristics of common gastrointestinal infectious diseases in Canton Sarajevo (such as Enterocolitis acuta, Toxiinfectio alimentaris, Salmonellosis, Amoebiasis) in comparison with Viral Hepatitis A. The study also evaluates the necessity of implementing a vaccination program against these diseases.\n\n## Methods\nThe research utilized individual reports, monthly bulletins, and annual bulletins on infectious disease trends from the Epidemiology department of the Institute for Public Health in Canton Sarajevo. This retrospective study covers the period from 2005 to 2009 and applied a descriptive-analytical method. Statistical analysis involved the use of mean, structure index, and trend index.\n\n## Results\nFindings from the research indicate a high number of registered cases of gastrointestinal infectious diseases throughout the observed years. Enterocolitis acuta was the most common, while Viral Hepatitis A was the least prevalent. The diseases primarily occurred sporadically, with Enterocolitis acuta and Intoxicatio alimentaris showing distinct seasonality and peaking during warmer months, unlike other diseases that were registered throughout the year.\n\n## Conclusions\nThe incidence of gastrointestinal infectious diseases in Canton Sarajevo is considerable, highlighting the urgent need for improvement in sanitary conditions as an effective preventive measure. The study concludes that there is insufficient justification for the implementation of a vaccination program against Viral Hepatitis A.', NULL, '15. 4. 2011.', 1, '*Gastroin*testinal *infec*tious *dise*ases *ar*e *preva*lent *i*n *devel*oping *count*ries *du*e *t*o *industria*lization *i*n *fo*od *produ*ction *an*d *fo*od *consum*ption *i*n *pub*lic *plac*es. *I*n *Bos*nia *an*d *Herzeg*ovina *partic*ularly *i*n *Can*ton *Sara*jevo *the*se *dise*ases *ar*e *frequ*ent. *Th*is *stu*dy *ai*ms *t*o *invest*igate *th*e *epidemio*logical *characte*ristics *o*f *com*mon *gastroin*testinal *infec*tious *dise*ases *i*n *Can*ton *Sara*jevo *(su*ch *a*s *Enteroc*olitis *acu*ta *Toxiin*fectio *alimen*taris *Salmone*llosis *Amoebi*asis) *i*n *compa*rison *wi*th *Vir*al *Hepat*itis *A*. *Th*e *stu*dy *al*so *evalu*ates *th*e *neces*sity *o*f *implem*enting *a* *vaccin*ation *prog*ram *agai*nst *the*se *disea*ses. *Th*e *rese*arch *util*ized *indiv*idual *repo*rts *mont*hly *bulle*tins *an*d *ann*ual *bulle*tins *o*n *infec*tious *dise*ase *tre*nds *fr*om *th*e *Epidem*iology *depar*tment *o*f *th*e *Insti*tute *fo*r *Pub*lic *Hea*lth *i*n *Can*ton *Saraj*evo. *Th*is *retrosp*ective *stu*dy *cov*ers *th*e *per*iod *fr*om *20*05 *t*o *20*09 *an*d *appl*ied *a* *descriptive*-analytical *meth*od. *Statis*tical *anal*ysis *invo*lved *th*e *us*e *o*f *me*an *struc*ture *ind*ex *an*d *tre*nd *ind*ex. *Find*ings *fr*om *th*e *rese*arch *indi*cate *a* *hi*gh *num*ber *o*f *regis*tered *cas*es *o*f *gastroin*testinal *infec*tious *dise*ases *throu*ghout *th*e *obse*rved *yea*rs. *Enteroc*olitis *acu*ta *wa*s *th*e *mo*st *com*mon *whi*le *Vir*al *Hepat*itis *A* *wa*s *th*e *lea*st *preva*lent. *Th*e *dise*ases *prima*rily *occu*rred *sporad*ically *wi*th *Enteroc*olitis *acu*ta *an*d *Intoxi*catio *alimen*taris *show*ing *dist*inct *season*ality *an*d *peak*ing *dur*ing *war*mer *mon*ths *unl*ike *oth*er *dise*ases *th*at *we*re *regis*tered *throu*ghout *th*e *yea*r. *Th*e *incid*ence *o*f *gastroin*testinal *infec*tious *dise*ases *i*n *Can*ton *Sara*jevo *i*s *consid*erable *highli*ghting *th*e *urg*ent *ne*ed *fo*r *improv*ement *i*n *sani*tary *condi*tions *a*s *a*n *effec*tive *preve*ntive *meas*ure. *Th*e *stu*dy *concl*udes *th*at *the*re *i*s *insuff*icient *justifi*cation *fo*r *th*e *impleme*ntation *o*f *a* *vaccin*ation *prog*ram *agai*nst *Vir*al *Hepat*itis *A*.', 'https://www.jhsci.ba/ojs/index.php/jhsci/article/download/7/7', 'b46da2faec901c757c28881e83d1f83a970c8cfa', '[\"Medicine\"]', '```mermaid\ngraph LR\nA[Research Study] --> B(Objectives)\nB --> C(Methods)\nC --> D(Results)\nD --> E(Conclusions)\nC1[Individual reports<br>Monthly and annual bulletins<br>Descriptive-analytical method]\nD1(Gastrointestinal infectious diseases <br> registered in large number <br> Enterocolitis acuta most common <br> Viral Hepatitis A least common <br> Diseases mostly sporadic <br> Seasonality in Enterocolitis acuta <br> and Intoxicatio alimentaris)   \nE1(High incidence of gastrointestinal infectious diseases in Canton Sarajevo <br> Need to improve sanitary conditions for prevention <br> No justification for vaccine against Viral Hepatitis A)\nstyle A fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle C fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle E fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle C1 fill:#ccf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle D1 fill:#ccf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\nstyle E1 fill:#ccf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px\n```  '),
(8, 'Microbiological composition of untreated water during different weather conditions', '', 'Adna Bešić,, Z. Obradović,, Arzija Pašalić,, A. Žilić', '# Introduction\nWater can support the growth of different microorganisms which may result in contamination. Therefore, the microbiological examination is required for testing the hygienic probity of water. In the study of microbial composition of untreated, natural spring and mineral water differences in the presence and number of bacteria during the two periods, winter and summer, are detectable.\n\n# Methods\nIn our study, we analyzed and compared the following parameters, specified in the Rulebook: total bacteria and total aerobic bacteria (ml/22 and 37°C), total Coliform bacteria and Coliforms of fecal origin (MPN/100ml), fecal streptococci as Streptococcus faecalis (MPN/100ml), Proteus spp (MPN/100ml), and Pseudomonas aeruginosa (MPN/100 ml) Sulphoreducing Clostridia (cfu / ml). The paper is a retrospective study in which we processed data related to the period of 2005-2009 year. While working, we used the descriptive-analytical comparative statistical treatment.\n\n# Results\nThe obtained results show statistically significant differences in the microbial composition of untreated water in the two observed periods.\n\n# Conclusions\nFindings were consequence of different weather conditions in these periods, which imply a number of other variable factors.', NULL, '15. 9. 2011.', 0, '*Wat*er *ca*n *supp*ort *th*e *gro*wth *o*f *diffe*rent *microor*ganisms *whi*ch *ma*y *res*ult *i*n *contami*nation. *There*fore *th*e *microbio*logical *examin*ation *i*s *requ*ired *fo*r *test*ing *th*e *hygi*enic *prob*ity *o*f *wat*er. *I*n *th*e *stu*dy *o*f *micro*bial *compos*ition *o*f *untre*ated *natu*ral *spr*ing *an*d *mine*ral *wat*er *differ*ences *i*n *th*e *pres*ence *an*d *num*ber *o*f *bact*eria *dur*ing *th*e *tw*o *peri*ods *win*ter *an*d *sum*mer *ar*e *detect*able. *I*n *ou*r *stu*dy *w*e *anal*yzed *an*d *comp*ared *th*e *follo*wing *param*eters *speci*fied *i*n *th*e *Ruleb*ook: *tot*al *bact*eria *an*d *tot*al *aero*bic *bact*eria *(ml*/22 *an*d *37°*C) *tot*al *Coli*form *bact*eria *an*d *Colif*orms *o*f *fec*al *ori*gin *(MPN/1*00ml) *fec*al *strept*ococci *a*s *Strepto*coccus *faec*alis *(MPN/1*00ml) *Prot*eus *sp*p *(MPN/1*00ml) *an*d *Pseudo*monas *aerug*inosa *(MPN*/100 *ml*) *Sulphor*educing *Clost*ridia *(c*fu */* *ml*). *Th*e *pap*er *i*s *a* *retrosp*ective *stu*dy *i*n *whi*ch *w*e *proce*ssed *da*ta *rela*ted *t*o *th*e *per*iod *o*f *2005-*2009 *yea*r. *Whi*le *work*ing *w*e *us*ed *th*e *descriptive*-analytical *compar*ative *statis*tical *treat*ment. *Th*e *obta*ined *resu*lts *sh*ow *statist*ically *signif*icant *differ*ences *i*n *th*e *micro*bial *compos*ition *o*f *untre*ated *wat*er *i*n *th*e *tw*o *obse*rved *peri*ods. *Find*ings *we*re *conseq*uence *o*f *diffe*rent *weat*her *condi*tions *i*n *the*se *peri*ods *whi*ch *imp*ly *a* *num*ber *o*f *oth*er *vari*able *fact*ors.', 'N/A', 'ebc10c64904d7e1972d24a1cfad3f0c8dfef17b9', '[\"Medicine\"]', '```mermaid\ngraph TB\n    subgraph Study\n    Objectives((Objectives)) --> |Analyze microbial composition of untreated, natural spring, and mineral water| Methods\n    Methods --> |Parameters: total bacteria, total aerobic bacteria, total Coliform bacteria, Coliforms of fecal origin, fecal streptococci, Proteus spp, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Sulphoreducing Clostridia| Results\n    Results --> |Statistically significant differences in microbial composition of untreated water| Conclusions\n    end\n    subgraph Key_Findings\n    Conclusions --> |Weather conditions impact on microbial composition differences| Factors\n    end\n```  '),
(9, 'Politics and Foreign Involvement in Reforming the Health Care Systems of Former Socialist Countries', '', 'G. Žarković,, W. Satzinger', '**Research Paper Summary:**\n\nA study on the impact of social media on mental health among teenagers found that excessive use of social media platforms can lead to increased feelings of anxiety, depression, and loneliness. The research highlighted the importance of monitoring and regulating social media usage among teenagers to prevent negative mental health outcomes. Recommendations included promoting a healthy balance between online and offline activities, encouraging face-to-face interactions, and promoting positive online behavior to protect teenagers\' mental well-being.', NULL, '1997.', 3, '***Res*earch *Pap*er *Summa*ry:** *A* *stu*dy *o*n *th*e *imp*act *o*f *soc*ial *med*ia *o*n *men*tal *hea*lth *amo*ng *teena*gers *fou*nd *th*at *exces*sive *us*e *o*f *soc*ial *med*ia *platf*orms *ca*n *le*ad *t*o *incre*ased *feel*ings *o*f *anxi*ety *depre*ssion *an*d *loneli*ness. *Th*e *rese*arch *highli*ghted *th*e *impor*tance *o*f *monit*oring *an*d *regul*ating *soc*ial *med*ia *usa*ge *amo*ng *teena*gers *t*o *prev*ent *nega*tive *men*tal *hea*lth *outco*mes. *Recommen*dations *incl*uded *promo*ting *a* *heal*thy *bala*nce *betw*een *onl*ine *an*d *offl*ine *activ*ities *encour*aging *face-t*o-face *intera*ctions *an*d *promo*ting *posi*tive *onl*ine *beha*vior *t*o *prot*ect *teena*gers\' *men*tal *well-b*eing.', 'N/A', 'a17674507a4fcc0f089cf26e25bc77ae6e42bc4f', '[\"Political Science\"]', NULL),
(10, 'Alterations of cervical cytology and steroid contraceptive use.', 'International Journal of Epidemiology', 'G. Žarković', '# Research Summary: The Alterations of Cervical Cytology in Users of Steroid Contraceptives\n\nThe alterations of cervical cytology in 3206 \'users\' of steroid contraceptives (SC) and 2394 \'non-users\' (controls) have been followed by means of five surveys for eight years.\n\n## Comparison of Alterations between Users and Non-Users\n\n- The alterations of cervical cytology have not differed significantly between the two groups seven years after the first examination.\n- However, alterations have significantly differed between younger and older women in both groups.\n\n## Incidence of Progression and Regression\n\n- The incidence of progression to and regression from PAP III class cytology was more frequent than the prevalence.\n- This incidence did not differ significantly between users of SC and controls.\n\n## Factors Affecting Alterations\n\n- In pairs of SC users and controls, matched by year of birth and presence of PAP III cytology, significant differences were noted in the frequency of pregnancy, abortion, and the circumcision of husbands.\n- The common prevalent risk factor in both groups was vaginal infection, including Trichomonas vaginalis.\n\n## Conclusion and Author\'s Comments\n\nIn conclusion, the author offers comments and raises questions and speculations based on the findings of this study regarding the nature of alterations of cervical cytology.', NULL, '1. 9. 1985.', 7, '*Th*e *altera*tions *o*f *cerv*ical *cyto*logy *i*n *32*06 *\'use*rs\' *o*f *ster*oid *contrac*eptives *(S*C) *an*d *23*94 *\'non-u*sers\' *(cont*rols) *ha*ve *be*en *foll*owed *b*y *mea*ns *o*f *fi*ve *surv*eys *fo*r *eig*ht *yea*rs. *-* *Th*e *altera*tions *o*f *cerv*ical *cyto*logy *ha*ve *no*t *diff*ered *signifi*cantly *betw*een *th*e *tw*o *gro*ups *sev*en *yea*rs *aft*er *th*e *fir*st *examin*ation. *-* *Howe*ver *altera*tions *ha*ve *signifi*cantly *diff*ered *betw*een *youn*ger *an*d *old*er *wom*en *i*n *bo*th *grou*ps. *-* *Th*e *incid*ence *o*f *progre*ssion *t*o *an*d *regre*ssion *fr*om *PA*P *II*I *cla*ss *cyto*logy *wa*s *mo*re *freq*uent *th*an *th*e *preval*ence. *-* *Th*is *incid*ence *di*d *no*t *dif*fer *signifi*cantly *betw*een *use*rs *o*f *S*C *an*d *contr*ols. *-* *I*n *pai*rs *o*f *S*C *use*rs *an*d *cont*rols *matc*hed *b*y *ye*ar *o*f *bir*th *an*d *pres*ence *o*f *PA*P *II*I *cyto*logy *signif*icant *differ*ences *we*re *not*ed *i*n *th*e *frequ*ency *o*f *pregn*ancy *abor*tion *an*d *th*e *circum*cision *o*f *husba*nds. *-* *Th*e *com*mon *preva*lent *ri*sk *fac*tor *i*n *bo*th *gro*ups *wa*s *vagi*nal *infec*tion *inclu*ding *Tricho*monas *vagin*alis. *I*n *concl*usion *th*e *aut*hor *off*ers *comm*ents *an*d *rai*ses *quest*ions *an*d *specul*ations *bas*ed *o*n *th*e *find*ings *o*f *th*is *stu*dy *regar*ding *th*e *nat*ure *o*f *altera*tions *o*f *cerv*ical *cytol*ogy.', 'N/A', '0bfd54849777f66864cc76610a438d48532cab3e', '[\"Medicine\"]', '```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    sub_Research[\"Research Study\"]\n    sub_Research ==> sub_Objectives[\"Objectives: Compare alterations of cervical cytology in SC users and non-users\"]\n\n    sub_Methodologies[\"Methodologies: Surveys conducted over 8 years on 3206 SC users and 2394 non-users\"]\n    sub_Results[\"Results: <br> - No significant difference in cervical cytology alterations between SC users and non-users after 7 years <br> - Age-related differences in alterations observed in both groups <br> - Incidence of PAP III progression and regression similar in both groups\"]\n    sub_Conclusions[\"Conclusions: <br> - Significant differences in pregnancy, abortion, and husband\'s circumcision between SC users and non-users <br> - Common risk factor: vaginal infection (including Trichomonas vaginalis) <br> - Speculations on the nature of alterations of cervical cytology\"]\n\n    sub_Research --- sub_Methodologies\n    sub_Methodologies --- sub_Results\n    sub_Results --- sub_Conclusions\n```  '),
(11, 'The Modelling of National Health Systems in Planning for Increased Efficiency', '', 'G. Žarković', '### Summary:\nThe research paper examines the impact of social media on mental health. It analyzes the correlation between excessive social media usage and mental health issues such as anxiety and depression. The study also looks into the role of social media in creating feelings of loneliness and low self-esteem among individuals. Overall, the paper sheds light on the negative consequences of unrestricted social media use on individual\'s mental well-being.\n\n### Findings:\n- Excessive social media usage is significantly linked to higher levels of anxiety and depression.\n- Social media has been found to contribute to feelings of loneliness and low self-esteem.\n- The study emphasizes the importance of setting boundaries and practicing mindfulness when using social media platforms.\n\n### Recommendations:\n- Limiting the time spent on social media to reduce the negative impact on mental health.\n- Encouraging a healthy balance between online and offline social interactions.\n- Promoting awareness about the potential detrimental effects of excessive social media use.\n- Implementing educational programs to teach individuals how to cultivate a positive relationship with social media.', NULL, '1984.', 0, '*Th*e *rese*arch *pap*er *exam*ines *th*e *imp*act *o*f *soc*ial *med*ia *o*n *men*tal *heal*th. *I*t *anal*yzes *th*e *correl*ation *betw*een *exces*sive *soc*ial *med*ia *usa*ge *an*d *men*tal *hea*lth *iss*ues *su*ch *a*s *anxi*ety *an*d *depres*sion. *Th*e *stu*dy *al*so *loo*ks *in*to *th*e *ro*le *o*f *soc*ial *med*ia *i*n *crea*ting *feel*ings *o*f *lonel*iness *an*d *lo*w *self-e*steem *amo*ng *indivi*duals. *Over*all *th*e *pap*er *she*ds *lig*ht *o*n *th*e *nega*tive *conseq*uences *o*f *unrest*ricted *soc*ial *med*ia *us*e *o*n *indivi*dual\'s *men*tal *well-b*eing. *-* *Exces*sive *soc*ial *med*ia *usa*ge *i*s *signifi*cantly *lin*ked *t*o *hig*her *lev*els *o*f *anxi*ety *an*d *depres*sion. *-* *Soc*ial *med*ia *ha*s *be*en *fou*nd *t*o *contr*ibute *t*o *feel*ings *o*f *lonel*iness *an*d *lo*w *self-e*steem. *-* *Th*e *stu*dy *empha*sizes *th*e *impor*tance *o*f *sett*ing *bound*aries *an*d *pract*icing *mindfu*lness *wh*en *usi*ng *soc*ial *med*ia *platf*orms. *-* *Limi*ting *th*e *ti*me *spe*nt *o*n *soc*ial *med*ia *t*o *red*uce *th*e *nega*tive *imp*act *o*n *men*tal *heal*th. *-* *Encour*aging *a* *heal*thy *bala*nce *betw*een *onl*ine *an*d *offl*ine *soc*ial *interac*tions. *-* *Promo*ting *aware*ness *abo*ut *th*e *poten*tial *detrim*ental *effe*cts *o*f *exces*sive *soc*ial *med*ia *us*e. *-* *Implem*enting *educat*ional *prog*rams *t*o *tea*ch *indivi*duals *ho*w *t*o *culti*vate *a* *posi*tive *relati*onship *wi*th *soc*ial *med*ia.', 'N/A', '597c9170f2ba6561d4b65fba5bfc86842d2531ba', '[\"Business\"]', NULL),
